{
  "target": "NumericalDerivative.gradient_element_quadratic",
  "kind": "special_function",
  "source": "Numerics/Mathematics/Differentiation/NumericalDerivative.cs; no dedicated Test_NumericalDerivative.cs exists upstream (grep-confirmed) and no other test file exercises Gradient/Hessian with a hardcoded literal, so every case here is curated.",
  "reference": "Numerics @ a2c4dbf. Closed function registry (must be implemented identically in core/tests/test_fixtures.cpp's numerical_derivative_{quadratic,normal_loglik} and tools/oracle_emitter/Program.cs's NumericalDerivative{Quadratic,NormalLoglik}): 'quadratic' is f(x) = sum_i (x_i - i)^2 (0-based i; analytic gradient 2*(x_i-i), analytic Hessian 2*I); 'normal_loglik' is Normal(mu=x0, sigma=x1).LogLikelihood(sample) on the embedded 5-point sample {9,10,11,12,13} (mean 11) -- the exact 2-parameter log-likelihood shape MCMC's default HMC/NUTS gradient differentiates. Args convention (this port's own): gradient_element_<fn> takes args = [p, theta(p values), lower(p values), upper(p values), index]; hessian_element_<fn> takes args = [p, theta(p values), lower(p values), upper(p values), i, j]. p is explicit; lower/upper always carry a full p-length bound array, using the fixture schema's '-inf'/'inf' string literals for unbounded dimensions (AvailableLeft/AvailableRight treat a +-infinity bound identically to a null one). rel_step/abs_step/max_backtrack always use the library defaults, matching every real call site. The '_near_bound'/'_pinned' cases exercise the bound-aware branch selection: near_bound cases set a lower bound within one default step of theta (forcing the forward-difference / one-sided-mixed-partial branch instead of central); the pinned case sets lower==upper==theta (zero room on either side), exercising the 'every backtrack attempt fails -> derivative set to 0' fallback. Every case's expected value was generated by running its inputs through tools/oracle_emitter --dump against the REAL C# NumericalDerivative and confirming the printed actual reproduces via verify_oracles.py.",
